<HEAD>Philip Honors War Dead in Simple Ceremony</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with Queen Elizabeth asking veteran
to end hunger strike over Philip's visit. Pickup 5th graf pvs, ``To many...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONIKA JAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YOKOHAMA, Japan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prince Philip of Britain, who has been
criticized at home for attending Emperor Hirohito's funeral, today
honored British soldiers who died in World War II by laying wreaths
at a cemetery.
   Accompanied by Foreign Secretary Geoffrey Howe, Philip honored
the 1,738 British, Australian and other war dead buried at the
Yokohama Commonwealth War Cemetery a day after attending the
elaborate funeral of Emperor Hirohito.
   In drizzling rain, the two British representatives laid wreaths
at a crucifix in the center of the rolling cemetery grounds and
later spoke with members of the local British community.
   In London today, Queen Elizabeth II appealed to a World War II
veteran to end his hunger strike protest over Prince Philip's
attendance at the funeral. There was no immediate reaction to the
latest appeal from Andrew Burgess, 70, who has been eating nothing
and drinking only black tea for the last nine days.
   Philip's attendance at Hirohito's funeral has been criticized by
British war veterans and lawmakers who considered the late monarch a
war criminal and who saw no reason to honor a man they blamed for
the deaths of thousands of their comrades. The royal family was
criticized for sending the husband of Queen Elizabeth II, and the
decision was debated in editorial columns.
   ``To many millions outside Japan, Hirohito will be remembered
less for the dignified last years of his reign than for its first
phase, when aggressive war was waged in his name and barbarous
atrocities were committed,'' The Times of London wrote in a January
editorial after Hirohito's death. ``To those people, the emperor's
passing will bring back painful memories.''
   Fighting under Hirohito's name, Japanese forces killed 27,000
British soldiers and another 20,000 Dutch.
   Many survivors also held Hirohito accountable for atrocities
committed against 127,000 Dutch people interned during the war.
   ``We are accustomed to hear such kind of criticism,'' said
Seizaburo Sato, a professor of political science at Tokyo
University. ``Japan made a mistake.''
   ``But didn't (the) British or Dutch do really bad things to
Asians they colonized, for example, India or Indonesia? If they
think about what they have done for a much longer period of time
than Japan did, I think they should be more modest,'' he said in an
interview.
   Most historians maintain that the late emperor was merely a
glorified figurehead of his generals with little, if any, political
power. Hirohito died on Jan. 7 at age 87, never having made clear
his role in the war.
   The cemetery is on the site of a playground that was opened by
Hirohito himself more than 65 years ago when he was crown prince.
   Nestled in the hills of Hodogaya in Yokohama, south of Tokyo, the
cemetery also holds the remains of soldiers from Canada, India, New
Zealand and other Commonwealth nations, and the ashes of an
undetermined number of U.S. soldiers.
   Many died while being held as prisoners of war in Japan or aboard
POW ships on the way to Japan in 1942 following the surrender of
Singapore. ``He loved his life but gave it in freeing the Japanese
people,'' read one epitaph.
</TEXT>
