<HEAD>Prince Philip Honors War Dead in Simple Ceremony</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONIKA JAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YOKOHAMA, Japan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's Prince Philip laid a wreath at a
war cemetery Saturday in a move to honor memories and appease
veterans angered that he paid last respects to Emperor Hirohito,
Japan's World War II leader.
   Philip, accompanied by Foreign Secretary Geoffrey Howe, honored
the 1,738 British, Australian and other war dead buried at the
Yokohama Commonwealth War Cemetery a day after attending Hirohito's
elaborate funeral.
   In light rain, the two British representatives laid wreaths at
the center of the rolling cemetery grounds and later spoke with
members of the local British community.
   British war veterans and lawmakers decried the attendance of
Queen Elizabeth II's husband at the funeral of the late monarch,
whom they denounced as a war criminal.
   In London, Queen Elizabeth II on Saturday appealed to one World
War II veteran to end his hunger strike, which was begun in protest
of Philip's attendance.
   There was no immediate reaction to the latest appeal from
70-year-old Andrew Burgess, who has been eating nothing and drinking
only black tea for the last nine days.
   Fighting under Hirohito's name, Japanese forces killed about
27,000 British soldiers and 20,000 Dutch troops. Many survivors also
held Hirohito accountable for atrocities committed against 127,000
Dutch people interned during the war.
   ``We are accustomed to hearing such kinds of criticism,'' said
Seizaburo Sato, a professor of political science at Tokyo
University. ``Japan made a mistake.''
   ``But didn't (the) British or Dutch do really bad things to
Asians they colonized, for example, India or Indonesia? If they
think about what they have done for a much longer period of time
than Japan did, I think they should be more modest.''
   Most historians maintain that the late emperor was merely a
glorified figurehead with little political power. Hirohito died on
Jan. 7 at age 87, never having made clear his role in the war.
   The cemetery is on the site of a playground that Hirohito opened
more than 65 years ago when he was crown prince.
   Nestled in the hills of Yokohama, south of Tokyo, the cemetery
also holds the remains of soldiers from Canada, India, New Zealand
and other Commonwealth nations, and the ashes of an undetermined
number of U.S. soldiers. Many died while being held as prisoners of
war or aboard POW ships on the way to Japan in 1942 following the
surrender of Singapore.
   At least one British war veteran attending the wreath-laying
ceremony thought Philip's visit to Japan was justified. The quick
trip to Yokohama was largely seen as an attempt to appease anger
over his attendance at the funeral.
   ``People are entitled to their own opinions,'' said Edward Ward,
77, who said he had served in Britain's intelligence corps and has
lived in Japan for about 10 years.
   ``But human rights would be in a sad state if people held grudges
forever more.''
</TEXT>
