<HEAD>First American Killed In WWII Honored 50 Years Later</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG MELLGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans and Norwegians on Saturday honored
a young army captain who became the first U.S. soldier to die in
World War II when he was killed in a German air raid.
   Capt. Robert M. Losey died April 21, 1940 at age 31 in the
central Norwegian village of Dombaas. He was on a mission to help
American civilians flee the April 1940 German invasion of Norway.
   U.S. and Norwegian officials and war veterans joined 400 people
for the ceremony in the village memorial park, laying a wreath on
an eight-foot-high stone monument marking his death.
   ``Capt. Losey's sacrifice was followed by the battle deaths of
292,131 Americans later in the war,'' said Loret Ruppe, U.S.
ambassador to Norway. ``Just as Captain Losey is now forever linked
to Dombaas, the United States and Norway are forever linked in
friendship and remembrance.''
   A native of Andrews, Iowa, Losey was killed when German bombs
exploded near a mountain tunnel where he had sought shelter. The
attack came nearly 20 months before the Japanese attacked Pearl
Harbor, which drew the United States into the war.
   A 1929 U.S. Military Academy graduate, Losey was buried at West
Point.
   Losey was an army air attache and aide to Florence Harriman, the
U.S. minister, or senior diplomat, in Norway. They were to lead the
evacuation of American personnel from Oslo to neutral Sweden.
   Losey, arriving from Finland, joined Mrs. Harriman near the
Swedish border and volunteered to go to Dombaas, an important
railroad and highway junction 150 miles north of Oslo.
   Losey felt the trip was too dangerous to risk a senior diplomat.
Dombass, a mountain village, was bombed heavily by the Germans
after an unsuccessful paratroop attack.
   During an air raid, Losey moved closer to the entrance to the
entrance of the tunnel he was in to observe the attack. One bomb
exploded near the entrance, killing Losey and several British
soldiers.
   Mrs. Harriman, who eventually made it to Stockholm, later said
the news of Losey's death ``was a horrible shock.''
   In the early days of the war, she wrote her ``sense of loss in
the world was centered in that one young American.''
</TEXT>
