<HEAD>Genscher: Obstacles to Unity Will Be Solved</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Baker, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher said
Wednesday the latest round of talks has left him confident about
solving the major stumbling block to German unification.
   The West German official, as part of the consultations aimed at
establishing the military stance of a united Germany, will meet with
Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze on Monday in the Soviet
town of Brest near the Polish border.
   The Foreign Ministry in Bonn said the two men will visit the
grave of Shevardnadze's brother, a Soviet soldier who died there
during World War II, as a sign of reconciliation.
   As Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev explains his nation's
wariness about a militarily powerful Germany, he has been reminding
Western countries of his 20 million compatriots killed during World
War II.
   East Germany's prime minister, Lothar de Maiziere, flew to Moscow
on Wednesday to take part in a Warsaw Pact leaders' conference, the
government in East Berlin said.
   De Maiziere will fly to the United States this weekend for four
days of talks that will include a meeting with President Bush.
   On Tuesday, Secretary of State James A. Baker III discussed with
Shevardnadze a package of Western concessions to try to win Moscow's
approval of NATO membership for the powerful new German state.
   Asked if they had made progress, Baker said: ``I think we did.''
   ``The area of mutual understanding on the complex issues seems to
be broadening,'' Shevardnadze told reporters at the Soviet Embassy.
   In an interview Wednesday, Genscher said he shared the
superpowers' confidence.
   ``I have a positive assessment of my talks with the American
secretary of state and the Soviet foreign minister, which went late
into the evening,'' Genscher added.
   Genscher told the Norddeutsche Rundfunk radio network he is still
hoping to present a German unification plan to a European summit
this year, saying he hopes the meeting can take place before
December.
   Genscher will fly to the Soviet town of Brest for the
Shevardnadze meeting Monday, the Foreign Ministry said.
   ``It was an invitation from Shevardnadze,'' said a ministry
spokesman. ``Shevarnadze's brother died there during the fighting.
Shevardnadze invited him to visit the brother's grave, which in
light of the past, is certainly not an unmeaningful gesture from the
Soviet side.''
   Asked whether the visit was meant as a sign of
``reconciliation,'' the spokesman replied ``yes, certainly.'' The
spokesman, asking not to be identified by name, said Shevardnadze's
brother died in June 1941 but did not know the fallen soldier's
first name.
</TEXT>
