<BYLINE>GIs, Soviet Vets Meet Again at Point Where WWII Armies United
^By MARK FRITZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORGAU, East Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviets and Americans met again by
the river Elbe on Wednesday, marveling at the imminent unity of
Germany exactly 45 years after they helped cut it in two.
   Under gray skies and a light drizzle, about 100 World War II
veterans watched a solemn ceremony as a wreath was laid in the
grassy river delta where the armies of two invading nations came
together.
   Soviet and U.S. veterans wearing medals from the historic
military campaign clasped hands, embraced and traded war stories in
the first Elbe reunion held on free German soil.
   Both armies invaded Torgau as they drove through Germany from
opposite ends, formally linking up April 25, 1945.
   William Robertson, 66, was credited with leading one of two U.S.
Army scout patrols that made the first contact with the Soviet
forces.
   ``To us veterans it's a very big deal, but it probably isn't to
most Americans,'' said the retired physician from Culver City,
Calif.
   ``But the Elbe meeting touches something very deep in the hearts
of the Soviets,'' he added.
   The last such reunion was in 1985 and drew about 25,000 people.
It was orchestrated by the Soviets and the then-Communist East
German government. The United States criticized it as a propaganda
extravaganza.
   The gathering Wednesday was more low-key and attracted a crowd
of only about 2,000 people to the river bank on the edge of this
aging town 75 miles southeast of Berlin.
   Veterans marveled at the peaceful revolt that ousted East
Germany's hard-line government. The popular uprising opened the way
for democratic government and eventual unification with West
Germany.
   The reunion Wednesday was planned in June 1989, when such events
were unthinkable.
   ``It's very confusing for some of us older people. There has
been a lot going on,'' said Soviet veteran Nikolai Sagoruko, 76, a
former member of a Soviet mine-sweeping force. ``But we think good
things are happening and hope it means peace.''
   Soviets turned out in their green Red Army uniforms, their
chests packed with medals and one little U.S. flag. Americans wore
baseball caps and blue-and-white jackets.
   Two small American scout troops made contact with two small
Soviet patrols along the river on that historic day in 1945, but it
was the group Robertson led that set up the meeting of commanders
from the two armies.
   ``The others were first, but we got the glory, the newspaper
clippings,'' said Robertson. ``They had communications problems and
nobody knew they made contact until the next day.''
   Retired Lt. Gen. Vladimir Orloe, leader of the Soviet veterans
contingent, said conflicting claims also existed between the two
Soviet patrols about which was the first to make contact.
   Ivan Krutcheno, 72, said he was part of the first group of
Soviet scouts.
   ``We came here and saw Americans and we thought we were in
America, we had traveled for so long,'' he said.
   The veterans gathered at a cemetery to lay a wreath at the
graves of Soviet soldiers killed in Torgau. They later placed a
wreath on the grave of Joseph Polowsky, an American soldier who won
unusual acclaim in the Soviet Union with his efforts to arrange the
periodic Torgau reunions.
   Polowsky, a New York City cab driver who died in 1983, insisted
he be buried at Torgau.
   ``He just thought it was so beautiful here,'' said Bill Beswick,
65, of West Point, Va., who was a pallbearer at Polowsky's funeral
and one of the first soldiers to reach the Elbe.
   Leonard Addorisio, 66, of Hartford, Conn., said he was amazed at
the camaraderie shown by the Soviet veterans.
   ``Everyone is so good, so friendly, you wonder why there are
wars,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

